                    "lastName": "Valdespino"
                },
                {
                    "creatorType": "author",
                    "firstName": "Vinicio J.",
                    "lastName": "Sosa"
                }
            ],
            "abstractNote": "Riparian forests are recognized as important ecosystems for biodiversity conservation in  12 transformed landscapes. Many animal species that use this type of vegetation facilitate its  13 recovery through pollination and seed dispersal. In landscapes dominated by agrosystems and  14 cattle ranching, persistent organochlorine pesticides (OCPs) in the riparian system may have an  15 effect on the physiology and fitness of animals. In this study, we measured bioaccumulation of  16 OCPs in the most abundant frugivorous bat, Sturnira hondurensis, from the upper part of La  17 Antigua basin, Veracruz, Mexico and, from these data, estimated accumulation by the frugivorous  18 bat community of riparian forests in contrasting, transformed (TL) and forested (FL) landscapes.  19 Concentration of ΣDDT, Σdrines, Σclordano, ΣHCH, Σheptachlor and Σendosulfan was measured by  20 gas-chromatography in 23 female and 33 male adult Sturnira captured during the dry and rainy  21 seasons. Using censored data statistics, we found that the sex of the individual was significant for  22 ΣHCH, and that interactions of landscape type (TL vs. FL) and season (dry vs. wet), and sex and  23 season were significant for Σendosulfan and Σdrines, respectively. Mean ΣDDT (6.86 μg/g) and  24 ΣHCH (28.22 μg/g) concentrations were lower than those reported for frugivorous bats in India but MANUSCRIPT  ACCEPTED  ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT  25 concentrations of Σdrines (13.86 μg/g) were higher than those reported in insectivorous bats. In  26 our study sites, frugivorous bats are bioaccumulating higher amounts of OCPs in TL than in FL. We  27 discuss the potential of this species as a bio-indicator of OCPs contamination in river basins.",
