            ],
            "abstractNote": "Bats are known reservoirs for several emerging diseases, and occur globally except for  Antarctica. There have been few studies that examine immune function in the Order Chiroptera,  particularly among natural colonies of bats. The phytohemagglutinin (PHA) skin test has been  widely used to measure the cell-mediated adaptive immune response in a wide variety of  vertebrates, and has been routinely employed in immunoecological studies. Although the test is  frequently described as a measure of T cell proliferation, recent studies indicate that it may  represent aspects of both innate and adaptive immune responses. Since the recruitment of  leukocytes is differentially, temporally and spatially regulated, we characterized the cellular  immune response to PHA challenge in bats by examining a time-series of histological sections  from PHA and saline injection areas in 41 Brazilian free-tailed bats (Tadarida brasiliensis).  Results suggest that bats exhibit a typical mammalian response, with diverse leukocyte traffic,  within 6 hours and up to 24 hours following PHA challenge. There was a significant presence of  lymphocytes and neutrophils, as well as eosinophils, basophils, and macrophages in PHAchallenged tissue, that was absent from saline control areas. We observed a highly significant  negative correlation between the number of lymphocytes and neutrophils in the PHA-challenged  tissue, with peak lymphocyte response at 12 hours post-challenge and peak neutrophil response  at 24 hours post-challenge. Results also indicate substantial variation in the immune response of  individuals, and may aid our understanding of disease emergence in natural populations of bats.",
